     AHR BROCHURE
     Date:  1 Dec 80



     COVER HEADLINE:                   Preparing for AHR

                                        Annual Hospital Report

                                        Tymshare Medical Systems

     INSIDE LEFT, SUBHEAD:             A Brief Background on AHR

     COPY:                                In 1974, the U.S. Congress passed

                                       Public Law 93-641 which established

                                       uniform cost accounting as one of

                                       ten national health priorities.

                                       Three years later, Congress passed

                                       Public Law 95-142 which amended the

                                       Medicare-Medicaid Anti-Fraud and

                                       Abuse Act to mandate uniform

                                       financial reporting by health care

                                       facilities within approximatly two

                                       years.  Then in October 1978, HEW's

                                       Health Care Financing Administration

                                       published a notice of proposed

                                       rulemaking for a System for Hospital

                                       Uniform Reporting (SHUR).

                                          "Uniform reporting systems for

                                       health services facilities and

                                       organizations" were officially

                                       proposed in the Federal Register by

                                       HEW in January 1979.  These proposed




                                     -more-









     AHR BROCHURE
     page 2 



                                       rules were sent out to a multitude

                                       of professionals in the medical

                                       field for comment.  The large number

                                       of comments received in response to

                                       the proposed SHUR regulations

                                       resulted in a revised version in

                                       March 1980.  This version proposes

                                       to establish an Annual Hospital

                                       Report (AHR) to document financial

                                       data, substantially reducing the

                                       cost and reporting burdens of SHUR.

                                          Although the final form that AHR

                                       will take is unknown, some form of

                                       uniform financial reporting for

                                       hospitals is probable in the not too

                                       distant future.




















                                     -more-









     AHR BROCHURE
     page 3 



     INSIDE RIGHT, SUBHEAD:            Preparing for AHR

     COPY:                                The reporting requirements that

                                       AHR would impose are meant to obtain

                                       comparable information on the costs

                                       and volume of services administered

                                       by all hospitals participating in

                                       Medicare and Medicaid programs.

                                       These requirements would mandate

                                       comprehensive statistical reports on

                                       revenue sources and costs of medical

                                       treatment by virtually all of the

                                       nation's hospitals.  The level of

                                       detail and sophistication needed to

                                       fulfill AHR's reporting requirements

                                       may well lead to the extensive

                                       revision of most hospitals'

                                       accounting systems - a chore that,

                                       if handled inhouse, would mean

                                       greatly expanded clerical staffs,

                                       equipment requirements, and

                                       professional consultant costs.

                                          Pilot versions of AHR have

                                       already been authorized and

                                       implemented by legislative and




                                     -more-









     AHR BROCHURE
     page 4 



                                       regulating bodies in cooperation

                                       with the Federal Government.  Some

                                       version of AHR is likely to emerge

                                       from the debates now being conducted

                                       by health care administrators and

                                       government officials.

                                          Health care administrators must

                                       consider ways to meet AHR

                                       guidelines.  The problem is to find

                                       an effective way to comply with AHR

                                       without exceeding operating budgets

                                       for administrative services.

     INSIDE RIGHT, SUBHEAD:            Tymshare Medical Systems:

                                       Offering a Planned Approach to AHR

     COPY:                                Tymshare Medical Systems is a

                                       leader in developing and offering

                                       applied computer services to the

                                       medical field.  As a major division

                                       of a leading international computer

                                       services company, TMS has the

                                       professional, technological, and

                                       financial resources to provide

                                       highly efficient automated services

                                       for the medical field.




                                     -more-









     AHR BROCHURE
     page 5 



                                          TMS creates these systems with an

                                       eye for long-range applications.  A

                                       flexibility is built into these

                                       systems that enables them to respond

                                       readily and conveniently to changing

                                       reporting requirements.  These

                                       comprehensive and flexible systems

                                       have long set TMS apart from other

                                       companies in its field.

                                          Specifically, TMS's Financial

                                       Control System (FCS), designed

                                       exclusively for the hospital

                                       industry, allows TMS to help health

                                       care administrators meet AHR's

                                       complex reporting requirements.  FCS

                                       provides these health care

                                       administrators with broad-based

                                       budgeting, forecasting, and

                                       cost-control tools.  FCS applies the

                                       full power of advanced electronic

                                       data processing technology to

                                       general ledger, financial reporting,

                                       budgeting, and cost allocation.

                                       With FCS, hospitals can capture




                                     -more-









     AHR BROCHURE
     page 6 



                                       expenses and report them one way for

                                       internal purposes and, at year-end,

                                       adapt to the AHR reporting method.

                                          FCS offers TMS clients the

                                       capability to comply with AHR

                                       requirements in whatever form they

                                       should take.  This brochure details

                                       some basic reports delivered by TMS

                                       systems and describes how they

                                       fulfill anticipated AHR

                                       requirements.  These reports can be

                                       quickly revised as government

                                       information requirements change.


























